Sign up to our Next Africa newsletter and  follow Bloomberg Africa on Twitter Ugandan pop star-turned politician Bobi Wine unveiled a political party, as he prepares to challenge President Yoweri Museveni in the February general elections. The party registered as National Unity Platform was acquired from its founders by Wine’s People Power movement, Joel Ssenyonyi, the group’s spokesman said by phone from the capital, Kampala. Wine, whose real name is Robert Kyagulanyi, sprung to prominence by singing about the plight of ordinary people and became a lawmaker in 2017. Today we unveiled the National Unity Platform (NUP), the political vehicle/party which the People Power movement will use going forward. Our symbol is the Umbrella. pic.twitter.com/19AnbExued The acquisition of the party followed concerns by People Power members who wanted a distinct “vehicle and symbol” since the group has individuals from other parties, Ssenyonyi said. Wine, 38, is among those who have announced plans to challenge Museveni, who has ruled Africa’s biggest coffee exporter since 1986. READ: Ugandan Pop Star Agrees Alliance With Veteran Opposition Leader